1. Find Domain-like strings.
 ([a-zA-Z0-9-]+\.)+ — matches one or more labels (like www. or mail.), allowing letters, digits, and hyphens
 [a-zA-Z]{2,63} — matches the top-level domain (TLD), like com, net, co.uk, etc.
 -Eo — enables extended regex and prints only the matched part
$ grep -Eo '([a-zA-Z0-9-]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,63}' file.txt
https://example.com
 
2. Find IP address in test.txt. 
-E: Enables extended regular expressions. -o: Outputs only the matched portion, rather than the full line.
 ([0-9]{1,3}\.){3} ==> ([0-9]{1,3}\.): Matches 1 to 3 digits ([0-9]{1,3}), followed by a dot (.).
 {3}: Repeats this pattern three times, ensuring we get three number-dot pairs.
 [0-9]{1,3} ==> Matches the final group of 1 to 3 digits, completing the IPv4 address structure.
 $ grep -Eo '([0-9]{1,3}\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}'
192.168.110.54

