$ echo "10.129.228.236 LAB.LOCAL" | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts
		tee = reads the input it receives from the pipe |
		-a = append
		Resolve name “LAB.LOCAL” → IPaddr  “10.129.228.236” 
# /etc/hosts = static name-to-IP mapping used for local overrides; checked before DNS
# /etc/resolv.conf = configures DNS servers for dynamic name resolution when /etc/hosts doesn't match
TL;DR: hosts is local and manual, resolv.conf is networked and dynamic.
$ sudo chattr -i /etc/resolv.conf
Removes the immutable flag so the file can be modified or deleted.
$ echo "nameserver 10.129.228.236" | sudo tee -a /etc/resolv.conf
Adds 10.129.228.236 as the first DNS resolver in /etc/resolv.conf so your system queries that server for name lookups.
$ sudo chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf
+i sets the immutable flag, preventing any changes, deletions, or overwrites — even by root.
