$ Journalctl -u <Service name> | tail -n 20		-> inspecting the last 20 log entries of a specific systemd service
• journalctl → Queries and displays logs collected by systemd-journald.
• -u <Service name> → Filters logs to only show entries from the specified unit (e.g., nginx.service, sshd.service).
• | tail -n 20 → Pipes the output to tail, which shows only the last 20 lines.

To list all systemd services (units) on your system, you can use:
🔧 Commands
• Show all loaded units (active + inactive):
$ systemctl list-units --type=service --all

• Show only active services:
$ systemctl list-units --type=service

• Show all installed service files (whether running or not):
systemctl list-unit-files --type=service

